[caption id="attachment_203001" align="alignleft" width="182"]<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/10/VGI-badge-rocket-camera.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-203001" src="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/10/VGI-badge-rocket-camera-182x300.jpg" alt="" width="182" height="300" /></a> Ring of Reconnaissance Rocketeers<br />5000 â 5999 points<br />The Maul Camera Rocket was developed by German engineer Alfred Maul in 1904. The Maul Camera Rocket was one of the first such devices that produced sharp images due to Maulâs innovation of using gyroscopes to stabilize the rocket and fins to prevent rotation of the rocket. The history of rocket cameras was short due to the development of the airplane.[/caption]

With the overwhelming response from dedicated volunteers it soon became apparent that additional categories were necessary.Â  The first volunteer to reach the highest recognition level, the <a href="http://navigator.er.usgs.gov/help/Rewards/Rewards_System/Reward_Categories/Theodolite_Assemblage.htm">Theodolite Assemblage</a>, did so on July 3, 2013 just two months after the start of the recognition program! We have now added four new categories that will be used to recognize the extraordinary effort of a handful of volunteers up to the 6000+ points achievement level.

[caption id="attachment_203011" align="alignright" width="150"]<a href="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/10/VGI-badge-airplane.jpg"><img class="size-thumbnail wp-image-203011" src="http://www.usgs.gov/blogs/features/files/2014/10/VGI-badge-airplane-150x150.jpg" alt="" width="150" height="150" /></a> World War I saw the first use and rapid development of airplane- based photographic reconnaissance, which proved to be the most reliable way to obtain aerial photography. Both sides of the conflict used aerial photographs to monitor the expansion of trenches and troop movements. From these activities during war time evolved the science of photogrammetry.[/caption]

The first set of recognition badges features antique surveying equipment.Â  The new recognition badges take to the air and are based on early aerial observation of the Earthâs surface.Â  Badges include the balloon that took the first aerial image, a pigeon with an attached camera, a rudimentary rocket, and a biplane with a cameraman leaning out the cockpit. Get more information about these icons by visiting the recognition badge pictures featured on this page.

Though there was some interest in using pigeons for reconnaissance purposes during both of the World Wars, the airplane proved to be more reliable. The use of pigeon-based photographs was most popular at fairs and exhibitions where individuals could purchase freshly produced aerial images in the form of postcards, some of which included the pigeonâs wingtips in the margin of the photograph.

The Maul Camera Rocket was developed by German engineer Alfred Maul in 1904. The Maul Camera Rocket was one of the first such devices that produced sharp images due to Maulâs innovation of using gyroscopes to stabilize the rocket and fins to prevent rotation of the rocket.Â  The history of rocket cameras was short due to the development of the airplane.

World War I saw the first use and rapid development of airplane- based photographic reconnaissance, which proved to be the most reliable way to obtain aerial photography. Both sides of the conflict used aerial photographs to monitor the expansion of trenches and troop movements. From these activities during war time evolved the science of photogrammetry<strong>.</strong>

